    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="some Hebrew on every line"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Rochester</placeName>, <date>Sunday, 3<hi rend="sup"
                        >rd</hi> of Iyar (May), 1857</date>.</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">A voice announcing on the mountains,</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">peace, peace to him who is far and</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">to him who is near, saith the Lord,</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">and to my loyal friend and dearly</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">beloved, the honored sir, a prince</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">and a humanitarian, choice spirit,</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">a man of understanding, learned in</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">all knowledge, searcher in language</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">and book, <persName>Eliesar Isaac</persName>, may his</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">name shine before the sun.</p>
            <p>Honored friend:</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Although I intend to undertake, during the course of the next
                win-<lb/>ter, God willing, a new, corrected, and improved edition of my Hebrew
                gram-<lb/>-mar, nevertheless I should like to get rid of the remainder of the
                former<lb/> edition. I have therefore lowered its price to $1.25. Have the
                goodness,<lb/> therefore, and enclose the advertisement here contained, in your
                worthy<lb/> journal, and I shall be very grateful to you if you can do something
                for<lb/> me in this regard.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Moreover, will you please send me 6 of your catechisms.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">There is no news. What do you think of the Baltimorean
                Christian<lb/> Sabbath? This is the end of all reformers. One begins with the <hi
                    rend="underline">Te-kum</hi><lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">Purkan</hi> and one ends with the removal of the heavenly yoke.
                But this is<lb/> the greatest advantage that orthodoxy can contain, for by this the
                eyes<lb/> of <placeName>Israel</placeName> will be opened, and he who dwells in
                heaven will laugh. Let<lb/> them do what they like. There is a time for everything
                and there is no<lb/> man who does not have his hour. I am firmly convinced that
                within hardly<lb/> ten years reform will be as despised as dirt and vomit and the
                abominations<lb/> will depart from this land. What do you say, my friend, that the
                false<lb/> has ceased from <placeName>Zion</placeName>? Would that be a
                    calamity?<add>?</add>. How has the daugh-<lb/>ter of <placeName>Zion</placeName>
                fallen from Heaven? May all their work be thus vain and void.<lb/> They shall build
                and I shall destroy, saith the Lord. What will the great<lb/> eagle/who soars over
                the impure nests of the city of <placeName>New York</placeName> do now? Not<lb/> in
                vain did the starling go to the raven, for they are a kind. Each bird<lb/> will
                dwell with its kind, and each man with one who is like him. Have you</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>also heard about the Emer Habazeleth (Valley of
                    Lilies—<persName>Lilienthal</persName>) in<lb/>
                <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName>, for his odor is gone and evaporated, and he has
                become like<lb/> a bare ruin in the desert.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In the hope that these lines will find you in the best of
                health<lb/> and hoping that you will be a bit disposed to do something about my
                gram-<lb/>mar, I greet you respectfully and say to you, Peace.</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)"><persName role="author">Mayer</persName>, son of
                    <persName>Moses</persName></p>
            <p>N.B.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Before <date>Passover</date>, I held a public school examination
                which met with<lb/> everyone's approval. There was also an exhibition which more
                than<lb/> 500 persons, mostly Americans of the highest circles here, witnessed.<lb/>
                I also preached on the <date>first</date> and <date>second day of Passover</date>.,
                the <del><date>Saturday</date></del><lb/>
                <del>of <date>Passover</date></del> and the <date>seventh</date> and <date>last
                    days</date>. The last I did purposely<lb/> so that the <date>second day</date>
                should not seem insignificant to them. I assure<lb/> you that our synagogue was full
                and crowded on each day, the <date>first</date> and<lb/>
                <date>second day</date> and the <date>seventh</date> and <date>last day</date>, in
                spite of the bad weather and<lb/> snow storms. I can say in the words of the
                Haftarah of the <date>second day<lb/> of Passover</date>, “Never has such a
                    <date>Passover</date> been celebrated here” in every<lb/> respect. My
                congregation has already reelected me at a higher salary<lb/> long before the
                expiration of my term. So much for today-more later.</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">Your friend,</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">
                <persName role="author">Dr. I. Mayer</persName>
            </p>
